issue(id="0007" status="open")
  title Automate the scrubs validation plan with canonical local probes
  user-story
    as-a scrubs maintainer changing bootstrap, auth, or dirty-boundary behavior
    i-want the documented validation plan encoded as repeatable scripts
    so-that regression checks can be run locally and on suitable runners without relying on memory or one-off terminal transcripts
  premise.
    Scrubs now has a clearer default validation plan: bootstrap a fresh guest,
    confirm repeat-bootstrap survivability, confirm clean-space auth works
    without login ceremony, confirm dirty-space visibility boundaries still
    hold, and confirm HTTPS Git still works through the scrubs-owned `gh`
    helper path.

    That plan is useful as an operator checklist, but it is not yet the kind
    of canonical artifact that can be re-run consistently across contributors
    or wired into automation. The product stack also has an important hosting
    constraint: GitHub-hosted macOS arm64 runners do not support the nested
    virtualization path needed for the real Apple Silicon `vz` story, so the
    full test plan cannot be treated as a standard GitHub-hosted CI job.

    The goal of this task is therefore not "make everything run on GitHub
    Actions immediately." The goal is to encode the known-good strategies into
    local-first, self-hostable test scripts with clear outputs, so the plan is
    rigorous before it is fully automated.

    We also now have several `try-*` project guests that act as lightweight
    validation fixtures for individual modules and compositions. This task
    should decide whether the canonical validation path reuses those guests as
    long-lived probes, replaces them with a more formal harness, or does some
    mixture of both.
  acceptance-criteria
    criterion Scrubs has one or more canonical scripts or commands that encode the documented validation baseline rather than leaving it as README-only operator prose.
    criterion The scripted plan covers repeat bootstrap survivability, clean-space auth smoke, dirty-space visibility smoke, and the HTTPS Git helper path.
    criterion The scripted plan is documented with clear assumptions about required host secrets, disposable guest names, and which checks are expected to be non-destructive.
    criterion The work explicitly distinguishes checks that can run on ordinary GitHub-hosted CI from checks that require local or self-hosted Apple Silicon `vz` capacity.
    criterion At least one maintainer-oriented path can run the scripted validation plan locally end to end and produce an understandable pass/fail result.
    criterion The validation design explains the role of `try-*` guests, including whether they remain as canonical fixtures for module-level smoke coverage or are superseded by a more formal test harness.
  review-items
    item(status="open").
      Decide whether the canonical test artifact should be a single orchestration
      script, a small command suite, or a mix of reusable probes plus a higher-level
      runner command.
    item(status="open").
      Decide whether the canonical baseline should include a guest-project
      Linux happy-path smoke such as `nu`, `node`, `ni`, and `rg`, because a
      guest can finish bootstrap successfully while parser-safe Nushell or the
      dirty-runtime execution path is still broken.
    item(status="open").
      Decide how host-secret-dependent checks should be handled, including
      whether there should be dummy-secret smoke coverage, opt-in live-secret
      coverage, or both.
    item(status="open").
      Decide how much of the scripted plan should eventually be wired into
      GitHub Actions versus reserved for local or self-hosted Apple Silicon
      runners.
